Pangolins are illegally traded at unprecedented levels around the world. A new report released this week by the Wildlife Justice Commission shows a staggering 206 tonnes of smuggled pangolin scales were confiscated between 2016 and 2019‚Äîbelieved to be only a fraction of the total actually trafficked. Facilitated by expanding transnational criminal networks, trafficking is driving the species to extinction.‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
Marimba, pictured here with her caretaker Matteo Mambe, is the longest surviving Cape pangolin in captivity. Although now safe at our partner @wildislife_zen, Marimba was rescued from the illegal trade at less than a year old. As the world's most trafficked mammal, pangolins are extensively poached for their keratin scales and meat.‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
To protect them and other trafficked wildlife, we need to break every link in the chain‚Äîfrom poaching, to trafficking, to demand. By supporting wildlife rangers and engaging local communities, we can identify and stop potential threats to stop poachers before they strike. Working with international customs and wildlife enforcement officers, we can prevent illegal wildlife products and live animals from being traded across borders. And by raising awareness about the dangers of buying animals and animal parts online, we can educate consumers and disrupt digital criminal activities.‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
On World Pangolin Day and every day, we must continue the fight to protect them. ‚Å†‚†Ä

Have you ever noticed how brown Christopher‚Äôs stripes are? #TruthAboutWhiteTigers Breeders will inbreed their tigers over and over trying to get the ‚Äúperfect white tiger‚Äù so they can exploit the animal for large amounts of money because of people‚Äôs obsession and curiosity about them. BUT what happens to the white tiger cubs that aren‚Äôt perfect? Those born with disabilities, or brown stripes instead of black, cleft pallet etc etc Those are considered ‚Äúthrow away cubs‚Äù. Breeders will sell them for cheap or worse (yes most likely kill them because to them, they‚Äôre not worth anything) Laws and legislation are so lax that breeders do not need to keep records of the numbers of cubs they‚Äôre breeding or what happens to the cubs when they get older! Read more about all of this on bigcatrescue.org and search for the Big Cat Public Safety Act to find out how you can get involved and hold breeders accountable or even better end all private ownership of big cats and the exotic pet trade. #BigCatPublicSafetyAct #whitetigers #tigers #bigcats #cats
